SIMPLE: putty
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Putty
<hw>Put"ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>pot⟦eacute⟧e</ets>, fr. <ets>pot</ets> pot; what was formerly
called <ets>putty</ets> being a substance resembling what is now called
<ets>putty powder</ets>, and in part made of the metal of old pots. See
<er>Pot</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A kind of thick paste or cement
compounded of whiting, or soft carbonate of lime, and linseed oil, when
applied beaten or kneaded to the consistence of dough, -- used in
fastening glass in sashes, stopping crevices, and for similar
purposes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Golf)</fld> <def>A ball made of composition and not
gutta percha.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Putty powder</b></col>, <cd>an oxide of tin, or of tin
and lead in various proportions, much used in polishing glass, metal,
precious stones, etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Putty</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Putty
<hw>Put"ty</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Putties</plw>
<pr>(#)</pr></plu>. <altsp>[Written also <asp>puttee</asp>,
<asp>puttie</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[Hind. <ets>pa⟦tsdot⟧⟦tsdot⟧i</ets>
ribbon, brace, tie.]</ety> <def>A kind of gaiter of waterproof cloth
wrapped around the leg, used by soldiers, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Putty</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Putty
<hw>Put"ty</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Puttied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Puttying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To cement, or stop, with
putty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Putty-faced</ent>⟦br⟧
